                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-10-29T15:45:07.300-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Bringing genetic medicine back from the dark ages"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-10-30T15:20:09.879-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>For the past 30 years, Clark Pan, vice president, biotherapeutics &amp;amp; genetic medicine technologies, AbbVie, has had a front row seat to the intriguing evolution of research in genetic medicines.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>The field, which focuses on using genetic information&amp;nbsp;to treat or cure disease, first emerged in the 1970s.&amp;nbsp;But as a young scientist in the early 2000s, Pan saw it enter a so-called dark age following a series of setbacks.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>However, recent approvals for rare genetic diseases and pivotal discoveries — like the&amp;nbsp;gene editing technology CRISPR and mRNA-based vaccines — have brought about a renaissance.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“People became true believers in the past 10 years when you started to see really dramatic impacts for patients emerging, like the blind being able to see again and babies who initially were not expected to live past age 2, now able to live much longer,” he explains.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Thanks to a wave of breakthroughs and ongoing investments, genetic medicines today are now more poised than ever to transform patient lives. We sat down for a Q&amp;amp;A with Pan to learn why and to explore how AbbVie is using genetic medicine technologies and platforms to find treatments, and potential cures, for patients.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_copy_copy_
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-10-06T11:00:24.554-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-10-06T11:00:24.554-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy_copy_cop
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825668]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-10-29T12:09:16.786-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Q: Let’s start with a foundational question. What's the definition of genetic medicine? "
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-10-30T16:47:20.674-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>It refers to genetic materials, meaning DNA or RNA, used to treat or cure disease. These materials work by modifying, silencing, or replacing faulty genes that drive disease or by instructing cells to produce proteins that can help fight disease.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>To create these therapies, you not only need genetic material but also a vector, or a vehicle for delivering genetic information. The most popular vectors today are viral-like vectors.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Viral-like vectors are proteins derived from viruses, such as Adeno-Associated Virus (AAV) and lentiviruses, that encapsulate and deliver genetic materials into patients’ cells.&amp;nbsp;While vectors can be derived from a virus, they can also be made from a polymer of chemicals. One example is a lipid nanoparticle, a type of vector also being studied in this field.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
